statement.p:
Sketch the region designated by each set of inequalities.

1 \le r \lt 3

0 \le r \le 2, ~ \dfrac{\pi}{6} \lt \theta \lt \dfrac{\pi}{3}

subsection.p:
 If we know the Cartesian coordinates of a point, we can compute the polar coordinates as follows.
x^2 +y^2 = r^2,~~ \text{so} ~~ r = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}
\tan \theta = \dfrac{y}{x}
To find the angle \theta, it is not enough to compute \tan^{-1}(\dfrac{y}{x}); we must choose the angle in the same quadrant as the given point.

ol.li:
To convert from polar coordinates (r, \theta) to Cartesian: 
      \begin{align*}
        x \amp = r\cos \theta\\
        y \amp = r \sin \theta\\
        \end{align*}

To convert from Cartesian coordinates (x,y) to polar:
    \begin{align*}
        \amp r = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}\\
        \amp \tan \theta = \dfrac{y}{x}\\
        \end{align*}

To convert from polar coordinates (r, \theta) to Cartesian: 
      \begin{align*}
        x \amp = r\cos \theta\\
        y \amp = r \sin \theta\\
        \end{align*}

To convert from Cartesian coordinates (x,y) to polar:
    \begin{align*}
        \amp r = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}\\
        \amp \tan \theta = \dfrac{y}{x}\\
        \end{align*}
